            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgUniverseTimeBigBang\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgUniverseTimeBigBang', '0%')\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: The universe across space and time (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e47f9367-a0b1-4395-b788-f9037ab2a943",
                     "text": "©ESA",
                     "page": "The Universe Through Space-Time",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### The Big Bang\n\nThe image in this section represents our current understanding of the history of the universe according to the Lambda-CDM model (<htcite0>).\n\n#### The First Ideas\n\nOur early conception of the universe did not include an expanding cosmos — the original models considered it static (<htcite1>).\n\nHowever, discoveries made by Edwin Hubble (<htcite2>) showed that this view did not match the observational data, and thus it needed to be revised.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e47f9367-a0b1-4395-b788-f9037ab2a943",
                     "text": "©ESA",
                     "page": "The Universe Through Space-Time",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "11311584-03d0-4c19-a807-28e5aaced8d0",
                     "text": "Kragh, H.",
                     "page": "pp. 5",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1af85131-52aa-49ee-8f9b-2409eb806900",
                     "text": "Hubble, Edwin",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1929",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: What Now?</b><br /><br />Imagine you are a scientist living in <htdate0>, when Hubble discovered that the universe is expanding. How would you react?<br /><br />a) You would say that all scientific models are wrong.<br />b) You would do nothing, waiting for others to research it.<br />c) You would try to understand the new data and propose models that better explain the universe.</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1929",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Different scientists responded in different ways — and some of these responses actually appeared before Hubble’s discovery (<htcite0>):\n- In <htdate0>, Alexander Friedmann demonstrated that Einstein’s equations allowed for a dynamic, expanding universe.\n- In <htdate1>, Georges Lemaître independently proposed that the universe was expanding, though not exactly in the way we understand it today.\n\nEven though these works were published before Hubble’s measurements, they were largely ignored until the <htdate2>s.\n\n#### Different Views\n\nOur understanding of the universe advanced when, on <htdate3>, George Gamow proposed that the universe began from an extremely dense and hot primordial gas (<htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nAlongside the idea of a beginning that evolved into the universe we see today, the steady-state theory also emerged. According to this theory, although the universe is expanding, its average density remains constant. Thus, it would have neither a beginning nor an end (<htcite3>; <htcite4>).\n\nThese different ideas, in an unusual twist, ended up giving a name to the model we use today.\n\nOn <htdate4>, during a BBC interview about the steady-state theory, Sir Fred Hoyle stated that the other model (then unnamed) was unacceptable — and referred to it three times as the “Big Bang.” That name stuck (<htcite5>).\n\n### How Do We Choose Between Models?\n\nWhenever there are different models explaining natural phenomena, we must determine which one best matches reality.\n\nThe only way to know whether a model is correct is through measurements.\n\nIn <htdate5>, Arno Penzias and Robert Wilson measured the cosmic microwave background radiation, which we understand to be the leftover light from the early universe (<htcite6>; <htcite7>).\n\nThese measurements were incompatible with the steady-state model but perfectly matched the predictions of the Big Bang.\n\nFor that reason, the Big Bang model is considered the most accurate explanation of the universe.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "11311584-03d0-4c19-a807-28e5aaced8d0",
                     "text": "Kragh, H.",
