            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: What Came Before?</b><br /><br />The Big Bang model explains the universe we see today — but was there something before it?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### What came first?\n\nThe most honest answer we can give is simple: we don’t know.\n\nThe oldest information we have about the universe comes from the cosmic microwave background radiation, which dates to about 400,000 years after the universe began — still far from the actual moment of the Big Bang itself (<htcite0>).\n\nJust as there have been different models to explain why the universe is expanding, there are also theories that try to describe its earliest moments (<htcite1>). To choose among them, we need new measurements. And if all of them turn out to be wrong, we can formulate new ones.\n\nIn other words, as Socrates taught us, the **only thing we know is that we know nothing** (<htcite2>; <htcite3>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "894d5917-f6ea-4e45-b79f-c27c42af0bf1",
